##On the Lantern Festival, stranded Wuhan residents did not return home

WECHAT betteryourlife2013

The feature introduces better your life, focusing on the better you and the better world that comes with it.

Let's have more fun in Wuhan! Please click on the top better â†’ click on the upper right corner"..."â†’"set as star"

As of today, more than 30,000 people have been diagnosed with NCP nationwide, killing 723, far more than the 2003 outbreak of SARS. The outbreak took place during the Spring Festival, a festival of great significance to the Chinese people, and brought separation, anxiety and tears.
Rising numbers are numbing the numbers. I worry more about the health and safety of my grandmother who caught a cold last fall than the numbers. I hear my mother say she went downstairs to buy medicine with a headache and a panic attack, i was afraid a virus was gonNA get in here.
This is my routine when I'm stuck at home in Yichang. But there are others, still stranded overseas, anxiously waiting for that sacred plane.
Today is the Lantern Festival, which is supposed to be a day of family reunion. For the stranded people in Wuhan, it is just another day of bewilderment and bewilderment. In their view, the road home has never been so long and tortuous, and the desire to return home has never been so strong.
Below, I recorded the experiences of five people in Wuhan who stayed abroad for more than 10 days.

I'm not a travel planner. At the end of the year, I just want to find a place to rest, read and sleep. I arrived in Chiang Mai on January 21, only to find that two days after my arrival, the city was sealed off.

I wanted to go home to have dinner with my mother on the afternoon of New Year's Eve. The situation forced me to travel from Chiang Mai to Bangkok. Only there was a chartered flight home.
Three days after I arrived in Chiang Mai, I began to think of two things. Where would I live? Buy A MASK! No matter where I went, I had to go to the drugstore every day to buy a few packs of face masks, and I realized that I should buy more. The clerk said there would be no more purchases, so I bought the remaining three packs of masks, which amounted to 1,000 yuan.

On the morning of the 25th, when I was resting, I refused to let the hotel aunt clean up. Thinking I was not feeling well, she told the manager of the lobby. About two hours later, an armed doctor came to me and asked me if I had been ill or taking any medicine, he asked patiently and carefully. It was a responsible thing to do, and I completely understood it.

After Wuhan was closed, I got an email cancelling my return flight because it was packed with summer clothes, so I thought of going to Sanya, Hainan, and from there to my other home in Haikou.

At noon that day, Haikou issued a document denying entry to Hubei People. The hotel soon expired, I quickly open flying pigs, where to find accommodation, some of the hostel owners see me is Wuhan number directly refused, and they are almost all Chinese.

So, I opened booking, began to search for foreign landlords, and soon found the current house.
Whether or not to go back, I struggled for a long time, it is impossible not to be afraid, in case to go back to encounter what situation, destroy the current balance? I didn't sleep all night on the day of the decision.

I was 81, personally experienced the 1998 flood, SARS period was isolated in the school, these memories are very deep, but not so special. There are difficulties, find some organizations we need to work together to solve, but many people only in slander questioned, I wonder why there is no basic trust in others?
I really feel how important it is to be independent, to filter information, to ask for help, and our education seems to have forgotten to teach people how to live.

My husband and I arrived in Paris on the 23rd, and as soon as we got out of the airport, we were surrounded by the media and asked, "why did you come to France? " At that moment, I was very angry, to be honest, and the experience made my feelings even more complicated.

Due to the escalation of the epidemic, the return flight on the 29th has been cancelled, contact the airport, the customer service telephone has been unavailable. I got in touch with Air France online and said I could change my flight to February 6th, only to be informed later that there would be no flights for the whole of February. Then I called the embassy diplomats every day to try to find a solution, and the response was, "it's expected. You don't have to ask every day. We don't have any information. Just follow the website. "
The third day began with impatience and no sign-up for us.
When I found out that I could charter a flight home, I called the British embassy again, and they said that the British would arrange it and would wait, but they couldn't guarantee it and suggested that I go home as soon as possible. On that day, airports across the country were still out of touch.
The messages I get every day are not sure, don't know, don't ask. Worrying about where you're GONNA live tomorrow? When can I go back? WHO SHOULD I call?
Later, my husband and I decided to lock ourselves in as if we didn't have to ask.
A student in Japan gave me a guide to return home. On the 29th, we got a ticket from Paris to Shanghai, then bought a ticket from Shanghai to Changsha, stopping at Wuhan, the best route. After the arrangements were made, we relaxed a little and spent two days in Paris.
To clear out the Louvre, for everyone's safety, we decided to go out at 6:00 to see the sights

But soon, the mood just recovered from the reality of the crit.
On the day of our return to China on February 3, the flight attendants learned that we were from Wuhan, and in order not to cause panic, they took our temperature and put us in the last row. All the seats in the previous three rows were removed and we were given separate tissues, the toilet is also used separately and tells us that there may be no service later.
At this time, a family of five people, one of the aunt asked why can not sit behind, the stewardess explained after their family's emotions exploded, began to heckle the staff, asked to get off the plane. This stalemate for an hour, the chief steward did not dare to make a decision, call headquarters, answer is do not want to fly off the plane, help change, the family of five before leaving.
The chief steward came over, arranged food for us, moved our seats to the window, and told us not to be afraid. He had experienced many such things during the SARS period. He also said, "I'm sure some passengers will ask, but I won't give away your information, " said a little girl in the front row, bringing a box of chocolates to comfort me.
Little Girl's chocolate

After landing in Shanghai, routine tests were clean, and after the luggage was disinfected, we were taken to the corresponding hotel isolation of China Eastern Airlines for two days.

But while we were waiting for our bags, a middle-aged man with a cellphone and a camera pointed at US said, "look, those are from Wuhan. "
Quarantine certificate

It wasn't until the wee hours of this morning that I finally made it back to my house in Wuchang and passed the third ring road in the same way as I always do in Wuhan at 3 or 4 am.
On New Year's Eve, my husband and I ate a bag of French fries at a fast food restaurant in France. That was our New Year's Eve dinner. Fortunately, I finally came back in time. There was Tangyuan in the fridge.

My job is between Wuhan and Thailand.
Because I am very familiar with Bangkok, there are some material channels. After the outbreak of the epidemic, after confirming the health of my family, I decided to stay here on my own initiative. First, I could reduce the burden on my family, and second, I could not help when I went back. Perhaps the people who stayed behind needed my help, i'm more useful here as a volunteer.
Recently, he has been assisting with the chartered flights for the repatriation of detained persons in Bangkok and has often served as a driver and porter.

With me is a girl from Hebei who has been working in Thailand and is the organizer of this work. We have a group of more than 300 people, who gather information about us, and post flight updates, and my job is to tabulate, feed back, respond, and keep an eye on real-time national and international publication policies.
Every day and every night we have to deal with a lot of repeated information, more than 300 people, one person, one sentence, the same questions are repeatedly explained, everyone is emotionally unstable, and even some people in the crowd spread rumors, questioning the airline company's profiteering, as the communicator in the middle, we are not only exhausted, but also under great psychological pressure.
Now the group is divided into two categories, one is concerned about home, outside the financial burden of important home people, most of them do not have any information source, also will not take the initiative to search and filter information, like headless flies like panic. The other part is already prepared to do not go back to the people, these people have rented a month of home-stay Villa, relatively calm.
One of the girls heard that F donated supplies, threw away half a suitcase to help them pack.

The number of Chinese stranded in Thailand has reached tens of thousands, and thousands of them are from Wuhan, so this has led to another phenomenon. First came the fear, then came the virus. This is a very delicate psychology.
In such a sudden disaster, to return to the overseas detention area personnel, there is a set of strict procedures. First, we need to help the embassy to collect the information of those who want to go back, submit it to the Ministry of Foreign Affairs for approval, and then decide which airline to send. Before that, we need approval from both Thai and Chinese sides.
In order to minimize the economic losses, the number of people over 100 will be the official aircraft dispatch, so in this case, if less than 100 people sign up, we will face a lot of criticism and criticism, I just want to do my best to do something, i didn't realize how hard it was to do a good deed.

On the afternoon of February 7,130 people from the group arrived in Wuhan safely by charter plane.

My mood is up and down every day because I have to connect with a large number of suppliers, often with chartered flights and medical supplies, and then without or not meeting the requirements. And, there is a point I want to tell you, do not believe wechat business, they have a large number of mouth masks are fake, now the situation is more impossible.
Many people also through group chat and I wechat help, they are very upset, these days while helping to comfort others, but also worried about their own, the next two months I will have no income. When the work is done next week, I plan to discuss with my team what to do next.

My boyfriend is British, and we're out with three of his friends. When we learned that our chances of returning home on March 1st were slim and that we would be out for another month or two, the first thing that came to mind was what about my three dogs?

I sent them to the pet shop on January 14th. Twenty days later, I paid a fee, 16 days, 2,900 yuan, and then another month, which was quite an expense.
We have spent more than 30,000 RMB since we came out, and now I go to the beach every day for free. No shopping, no eating out, eating out at the street stalls, going to the convenience store to get a drink if you want, and then standing in front of the bar. In this way, the daily expenditure is controlled in 200 yuan or so, after all, I have no income now.
When they found out we were from China, they said, "well, here's to the virus. ".

I couldn't go back home, and I was worried about being infected when I returned home. My boyfriend offered to stay at his home for a while, which was also relatively safe. I also had a British visa in hand, so we bought plane tickets from Indonesia to Amsterdam and then to London, but his family's worried about getting infected, so to be honest, if I had a choice, I'd go back.
Financially, my boyfriend could work as a temporary worker in London, but I was embarrassed because I was from Wuhan, and I didn't know when the epidemic would end, which made it impossible for me to find a part time job, so I had to look online for jobs like teaching English, we have to make money.
Floating on the sea today, I said to this piece of sea: Pray for nature to take away this disaster.

There was a strong sense of flight, a sense of uncertainty, and the fear of being deported when I arrived in the UK, and I've been scouring immigration policy and official news every day for the last few days.
Later, I went to a store to buy slippers. When I paid for them, I showed a card with Chinese characters on it. The clerk asked me, "are you from Wuhan? " I unconsciously shook my head and said no. At Kuta, we passed a pub with a band at the door, and when the boss asked where we were from, I said Wuhan, and he said, "come and play with us, cheers! " It was the only time I was free from anxiety.
These two days when I went for a walk by the sea, I was thinking about the future of my life. The special experience changed my way of thinking.

The day before yesterday, I took a train from downtown ÅŒsaka to the suburbs to save money on accommodation. With the cleaning fee and taxes, I need to keep the cost under 150 yuan.
Along the way, I did not take out my cell phone, I also tried to speak Japanese in public, do not want others to see the screen in Chinese, my heart for me to panic, cause unnecessary embarrassment and trouble. Even when I pay, I count the change in advance, so as to avoid communication, seemingly simple action behind a very complex psychological activities, the Japanese do not like to bother others?
This is what it feels like to be in exile.
I have been out for more than half a month, eating at convenience stores and noodle shops every day for 600 yen, or about 40 yuan. I saw a shop selling Shanghai Chow Mein the other day, so I rushed over and bought a box. It's not delicious, to be honest, but it's the closest thing to home that tastes Chinese.

I was once at an exhibition at a museum, and I was practically sweating when the host asked where everyone was from. The fact that I am from Wuhan, I say or do not say, all feel bad, this feeling is unprecedented.

Yesterday, just moved to the suburbs, passing a thin stream, saw a white crane, surrounded by low cottage houses, everything is quiet, transparent, anxious for a few days, mood suddenly become relaxed.
I saw on the Internet that there is a shop in Xi'an, which is said to be very delicious. I plan to go there tomorrow, mainly to chat with the boss, I want to talk to someone, because it is a person out, I haven't talked for a long time.

I heard that the early cherry trees on the Sanpu coast of Kanagawa Prefecture are already in bloom. What about the Cherry Blossoms in Wuhan?
My family and I run a small business in Hankou that doesn't make much money, and this time its fate is even more uncertain. But now I have to wait and see. What can I do in a hurry to get back? It's just GONNA get us in trouble. I think Wuhan people are very strong, will always try to create conditions to solve the difficulties, I can do is to start after the race to run.

Knowing that all the domestic trains to Wuhan are out of service, I still search for train tickets on the Internet every day where to go. I did not expect that such an independent person would be so homesick now.
"I hope to go home before the Lantern Festival, " I wrote in the time column of the Return Charter plane.

Yesterday, just moved to the suburbs, passing a thin stream, saw a white crane, surrounded by low cottage houses, everything is quiet, transparent, anxious for a few days, mood suddenly become relaxed.
I saw on the Internet that there is a shop in Xi'an, which is said to be very delicious. I plan to go there tomorrow, mainly to chat with the boss, I want to talk to someone, because it is a person out, I haven't talked for a long time.

I heard that the early cherry trees on the Sanpu coast of Kanagawa Prefecture are already in bloom. What about the Cherry Blossoms in Wuhan?
My family and I run a small business in Hankou that doesn't make much money, and this time its fate is even more uncertain. But now I have to wait and see. What can I do in a hurry to get back? It's just GONNA get us in trouble. I think Wuhan people are very strong, will always try to create conditions to solve the difficulties, I can do is to start after the race to run.

Knowing that all the domestic trains to Wuhan are out of service, I still search for train tickets on the Internet every day where to go. I did not expect that such an independent person would be so homesick now.
"I hope to go home before the Lantern Festival, " I wrote in the time column of the Return Charter plane.

My husband and I arrived in Paris on the 23rd, and as soon as we got out of the airport, we were surrounded by the media and asked, "why did you come to France? " At that moment, I was very angry, to be honest, and the experience made my feelings even more complicated.

Due to the escalation of the epidemic, the return flight on the 29th has been cancelled, contact the airport, the customer service telephone has been unavailable. I got in touch with Air France online and said I could change my flight to February 6th, only to be informed later that there would be no flights for the whole of February. Then I called the embassy diplomats every day to try to find a solution, and the response was, "it's expected. You don't have to ask every day. We don't have any information. Just follow the website. "

The third day began with impatience and no sign-up for us.

When I found out that I could charter a flight home, I called the British embassy again, and they said that the British would arrange it and would wait, but they couldn't guarantee it and suggested that I go home as soon as possible. On that day, airports across the country were still out of touch.

The messages I get every day are not sure, don't know, don't ask. Worrying about where you're GONNA live tomorrow? When can I go back? WHO SHOULD I call?

Later, my husband and I decided to lock ourselves in as if we didn't have to ask.

A student in Japan gave me a guide to return home. On the 29th, we got a ticket from Paris to Shanghai, then bought a ticket from Shanghai to Changsha, stopping at Wuhan, the best route. After the arrangements were made, we relaxed a little and spent two days in Paris.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
To clear out the Louvre, for everyone's safety, we decided to go out at 6:00 to see the sights

But soon, the mood just recovered from the reality of the crit.

On the day of our return to China on February 3, the flight attendants learned that we were from Wuhan, and in order not to cause panic, they took our temperature and put us in the last row. All the seats in the previous three rows were removed and we were given separate tissues, the toilet is also used separately and tells us that there may be no service later.

At this time, a family of five people, one of the aunt asked why can not sit behind, the stewardess explained after their family's emotions exploded, began to heckle the staff, asked to get off the plane. This stalemate for an hour, the chief steward did not dare to make a decision, call headquarters, answer is do not want to fly off the plane, help change, the family of five before leaving.

The chief steward came over, arranged food for us, moved our seats to the window, and told us not to be afraid. He had experienced many such things during the SARS period. He also said, "I'm sure some passengers will ask, but I won't give away your information, " said a little girl in the front row, bringing a box of chocolates to comfort me.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Little Girl's chocolate

After landing in Shanghai, routine tests were clean, and after the luggage was disinfected, we were taken to the corresponding hotel isolation of China Eastern Airlines for two days.

But while we were waiting for our bags, a middle-aged man with a cellphone and a camera pointed at US said, "look, those are from Wuhan. "

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Quarantine certificate

It wasn't until the wee hours of this morning that I finally made it back to my house in Wuchang and passed the third ring road in the same way as I always do in Wuhan at 3 or 4 am.

On New Year's Eve, my husband and I ate a bag of French fries at a fast food restaurant in France. That was our New Year's Eve dinner. Fortunately, I finally came back in time. There was Tangyuan in the fridge.

My job is between Wuhan and Thailand.

Because I am very familiar with Bangkok, there are some material channels. After the outbreak of the epidemic, after confirming the health of my family, I decided to stay here on my own initiative. First, I could reduce the burden on my family, and second, I could not help when I went back. Perhaps the people who stayed behind needed my help, i'm more useful here as a volunteer.

Recently, he has been assisting with the chartered flights for the repatriation of detained persons in Bangkok and has often served as a driver and porter.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
With me is a girl from Hebei who has been working in Thailand and is the organizer of this work. We have a group of more than 300 people, who gather information about us, and post flight updates, and my job is to tabulate, feed back, respond, and keep an eye on real-time national and international publication policies.

Every day and every night we have to deal with a lot of repeated information, more than 300 people, one person, one sentence, the same questions are repeatedly explained, everyone is emotionally unstable, and even some people in the crowd spread rumors, questioning the airline company's profiteering, as the communicator in the middle, we are not only exhausted, but also under great psychological pressure.

Now the group is divided into two categories, one is concerned about home, outside the financial burden of important home people, most of them do not have any information source, also will not take the initiative to search and filter information, like headless flies like panic. The other part is already prepared to do not go back to the people, these people have rented a month of home-stay Villa, relatively calm.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
One of the girls heard that F donated supplies, threw away half a suitcase to help them pack.

The number of Chinese stranded in Thailand has reached tens of thousands, and thousands of them are from Wuhan, so this has led to another phenomenon. First came the fear, then came the virus. This is a very delicate psychology.

In such a sudden disaster, to return to the overseas detention area personnel, there is a set of strict procedures. First, we need to help the embassy to collect the information of those who want to go back, submit it to the Ministry of Foreign Affairs for approval, and then decide which airline to send. Before that, we need approval from both Thai and Chinese sides.

In order to minimize the economic losses, the number of people over 100 will be the official aircraft dispatch, so in this case, if less than 100 people sign up, we will face a lot of criticism and criticism, I just want to do my best to do something, i didn't realize how hard it was to do a good deed.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On the afternoon of February 7,130 people from the group arrived in Wuhan safely by charter plane.

My mood is up and down every day because I have to connect with a large number of suppliers, often with chartered flights and medical supplies, and then without or not meeting the requirements. And, there is a point I want to tell you, do not believe wechat business, they have a large number of mouth masks are fake, now the situation is more impossible.

Many people also through group chat and I wechat help, they are very upset, these days while helping to comfort others, but also worried about their own, the next two months I will have no income. When the work is done next week, I plan to discuss with my team what to do next.

My boyfriend is British, and we're out with three of his friends. When we learned that our chances of returning home on March 1st were slim and that we would be out for another month or two, the first thing that came to mind was what about my three dogs?

I sent them to the pet shop on January 14th. Twenty days later, I paid a fee, 16 days, 2,900 yuan, and then another month, which was quite an expense.

We have spent more than 30,000 RMB since we came out, and now I go to the beach every day for free. No shopping, no eating out, eating out at the street stalls, going to the convenience store to get a drink if you want, and then standing in front of the bar. In this way, the daily expenditure is controlled in 200 yuan or so, after all, I have no income now.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
When they found out we were from China, they said, "well, here's to the virus. ".

I couldn't go back home, and I was worried about being infected when I returned home. My boyfriend offered to stay at his home for a while, which was also relatively safe. I also had a British visa in hand, so we bought plane tickets from Indonesia to Amsterdam and then to London, but his family's worried about getting infected, so to be honest, if I had a choice, I'd go back.

Financially, my boyfriend could work as a temporary worker in London, but I was embarrassed because I was from Wuhan, and I didn't know when the epidemic would end, which made it impossible for me to find a part time job, so I had to look online for jobs like teaching English, we have to make money.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Floating on the sea today, I said to this piece of sea: Pray for nature to take away this disaster.

There was a strong sense of flight, a sense of uncertainty, and the fear of being deported when I arrived in the UK, and I've been scouring immigration policy and official news every day for the last few days.

Later, I went to a store to buy slippers. When I paid for them, I showed a card with Chinese characters on it. The clerk asked me, "are you from Wuhan? " I unconsciously shook my head and said no. At Kuta, we passed a pub with a band at the door, and when the boss asked where we were from, I said Wuhan, and he said, "come and play with us, cheers! " It was the only time I was free from anxiety.

These two days when I went for a walk by the sea, I was thinking about the future of my life. The special experience changed my way of thinking.

The day before yesterday, I took a train from downtown ÅŒsaka to the suburbs to save money on accommodation. With the cleaning fee and taxes, I need to keep the cost under 150 yuan.

Along the way, I did not take out my cell phone, I also tried to speak Japanese in public, do not want others to see the screen in Chinese, my heart for me to panic, cause unnecessary embarrassment and trouble. Even when I pay, I count the change in advance, so as to avoid communication, seemingly simple action behind a very complex psychological activities, the Japanese do not like to bother others?

This is what it feels like to be in exile.

I have been out for more than half a month, eating at convenience stores and noodle shops every day for 600 yen, or about 40 yuan. I saw a shop selling Shanghai Chow Mein the other day, so I rushed over and bought a box. It's not delicious, to be honest, but it's the closest thing to home that tastes Chinese.
